Adenovirus infections occur frequently as documented by the presence of antibodies to one or more adenovirus serotypes in approximately 50% of infants and nearly 100% of adults [9, 10, 11]. In the face of these infections, disease in immunocompetent individuals is uncommon and rarely fatal owing to potent innate and adaptive immune responses. However, in the susceptible minority, particularly the pediatric age group, military recruits and those immunosuppressed either for transplantation and cancer or by HIV infection, disease is more common (Table 2
, Figure 1
).
